            <subject>Slide 21: Subtracting infinities</subject>
            <message>&lt;p&gt;Sir,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You have said that if the eigenvectors of A are outside the unit circle, e(m) will be a difference of two terms that both individually tend to infinity. How are we then deducing that their difference tends to infinity as well? For instance, if e(m) is a difference of f(x+1) -f(x), where f(x) = x, f tends to infinity for both terms as x and x+1 both tend to infinity, but the difference remains constant. Is there something more that allows us to definitely say that the error is blowing up?&lt;/p&gt;</message>
