            <userid>31087</userid>
            <created>1364136346</created>
            <modified>1364136742</modified>
            <mailed>1</mailed>
            <subject>Re: Slide 21: Subtracting infinities</subject>
            <message>&lt;p&gt;I could have given a better explanation in the slide.  We can write the equation for e(m+1) as follows: $$e(m) = A^m e(0) + \cdots$$.  As $$A$$ has eigen values outside the unit circle, $$e$$ will be unbounded if $$e(0) \neq 0$$.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please also note that $$e(0)$$ will necessarily have to be nonzero.  If it is zero, it would imply that we know the initial state exactly, using which we can calculate all the future states "exactly".  We are building an estimator precisely because we do not know the states "exactly".  In other words, we do not know the initial state and hence $$e(0)$$ will necessarily have to be nonzero.&lt;/p&gt;</message>
